>>127221523
The Bantu expansion happens out of the area of the Niger River area some time during the first Millennium BC. They were farming people (food surpluses from farming enabled their expansion), and spread this practice throughout the equatorial and sub-equatorial regions of Africa. Before the end of the 1st Millennium AD, they'd reached the Southern Cape. (They also displaced and genocided the pre-existing hunter-gatherer populations of the equatorial forests and sub-equatoreal savannahs, but that's a different discussion). East Africa had already had farming for a longer time, due to contact with foreigners along the Nile river and Indian Ocean/Red Sea. Most likely it was introduced into East Africa by a migration of middle easterners during the late Neolithic or early Bronze Age. In regions too dry, pastoralism would have prevailed instead of farming. Hunter-gatherers would have still existed in jungle regions, as well as the Kalahari Desert.

SS-Africa may have been comparatively undeveloped, but you still had settled societies, occasionally with a good deal of centralized leadership.

Ever since the Lotto's inception, if you are a feeder team, the draft is a cope. It is a tease. There's a reason it is a "lotto" - commonly known as a tax for the poor. You are gambling that you'll get a top pick and then gambling a pick isn't a bust, and then hoping to do that 2-3 years in a row. Giannis is the only drafted player since the rest of the league caught on to the Spurs strategy of drafting internationally to elevate a feeder team to a championship. That's not to say the draft doesn't matter. The draft matters a lot to the non-feeder teams since players are actually consistently loyal to nicer market teams unless the ownership is notoriously bad. If you draft a player in a good market, he's now yours as long as you want him. That's certainly valuable.
